<DOC><DOCNO> AP901011-0032 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-10-11-90 0231EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-ChessShowdown     10-11 0189</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Chess Showdown,0205</SECOND><HEAD>Kasparov Beats Karpov in Second Game</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Chess Notation, PM-Chess Algebraic</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Defending champion Garry Kasparov goes into thethird game of the world chess championship with a 1-point lead overAnatoly Karpov after defeating the challenger in the second game.   Karpov resigned on his 44th move Wednesday night about fivehours after the game started.   Kasparov now leads 1{ points to { point in the best-of-24-gamematch. The third game is Friday.   Kasparov, 27, who is the highest-rated player in the history ofchess, had the white pieces and the slight advantage of having thefirst move Wednesday night against arch-rival Karpov.   Kasparov, known for his bold, attacking style, and Karpov, 39,who favors methodical, defense-minded strategies, opened theirlong-awaited match Monday night. After five hours and 30 movesapiece, their first game ended in a draw.   Kasparov and Karpov last met for the championship in 1987. Itended in a tie, allowing Kasparov to retain the title he hadsnatched from Karpov in 1985.   This year's tournament will feature 12 games in New York and 12in Lyon, France. The winner will receive $1.7 million and the loser$1.3 million.</TEXT></DOC>